(89, 'BTU-3F4E1FAB', 15, 'Mr.', 'Amoah', 'Christian Cash', 'ccash5270@gmail.com', '+233552916040', 'Box 10\r\nBreman Essiam \r\nCentral Region', 'Ajumako', 'Breman Essiam', 'Central', 'Ghanaian', 'Christian', 'single', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'GHA-719626455-1', '1991-11-08', 'male', 'Master\'s Degree (Other)', 'University of Education, Winneba', 3, NULL, NULL, 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'Reading and watching football', '1 week', NULL, 'Mrs. Vera Ayitey, Ph.D', 'Senior Lecturer', 'Head of Human Resources Department', 'University of Education \r\nWinneba', '+233244058885', 'vaayitey@uew.edu.gh', 'Hillary Agbenosi (Rev.Fr)', 'Lecturer', NULL, 'St Paul\'s Catholic Seminary \r\nSowutuom \r\nAccra', '+233243789549', 'hagbenosi@yahoo.com', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'BTU_3F4E1FAB_cv_6a15a2582e7363.03315530.pdf', 'CHRISTIAN C. AMOAH- RESUME.pdf', 'pending', NULL, '154.161.4.215', '2026-05-26 13:38:32', '2026-06-07 23:59:41', 'BTU_3F4E1FAB_photo_6a15a2582e73c2.36376570.jpg', '1000000702.jpg'),
(90, 'BTU-112006F1', 3, 'Mr.', 'BAFIILE', 'EMMANUEL', 'bafiileemmanuel25@gmail.com', '+233540234069', 'Deeper Life Compus Fellowship, P. O. Box Up 1124, KNUST, Kumasi, Ghana', 'Maase Offinso', 'Tendoma', 'Upper West', 'Ghanaian', 'Christian', 'single', NULL, NULL, 'N/A', 'P002478043X', 'GH-717546957-5', '1997-09-27', 'male', 'Master\'s Degree (MPhil.)', 'Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology', 5, 'Manuscript currently under review by the Journal of the Ghana Institution of Engineering. \r\nEmmanuel Bafiile, Newton K. Amaglo, Ebenezer Ntiri, Isaac K. Boah, Obed O. Boahen, and Emmanuel \r\nAtiah. 2025. \r\nEffects of Biostimulants on the Growth, Yield, and Quality of Moringa oleifera Lam. in a Square Foot \r\nGarden. Paper presented under the sub-theme Climate Smart Agriculture Systems at the 56th Annual \r\nGeneral Meeting and Conference of the Ghana Institution of Engineering, held at Volta Serene Hotel, Ho, \r\nGhana, 17 March 2026. Conference theme: Engineering the Food Security and Sustainable Agriculture \r\nValue Chain.', 'My academic background, teaching experience, research activities, and professional practice aligned with the position of lecturer at the Agricultural Engineering Department of Bolga Technical University (BTU).\r\nI hold an MPhil in Vegetable Crops Production and a BSc in Agriculture from the Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology, Kumasi and Postgraduate Diploma in Education from the University of Skills Training and Entrepreneurial Development, Kumasi, and I am currently studying a PhD programme in Food and Post Harvest Engineering at KNUST. These trainings has equipped me with advanced knowledge in crop production systems, post harvest physiology and technology, food quality management, storage technologies and value addition which are direct relevant to applied agricultural engineering education.\r\nMy teaching experience which includes Teaching assistant and Graduate assistant involved lecture support, facilitation of field and laboratory practicals, student supervision, marking and grading and academic mentoring. These roles strengthened my ability to deliver competency-based and student-centred instruction suitable for Technical University training. \r\nMy research interest focus on climate-smart Agriculture, horticultural crops improvement, postharvest quality and shelf life, indigenous vegetable production and quality management, storage technologies, biotics and abiotic factors and their influence on post harvest quality of crop products, soil fertility management and organic amendments, urban and peri-urban production systems and inclusive agricultural development. These areas align perfectly with reducing post harvest losses, improving crop productivity and strengthening agricultural value chains. \r\nProfessionally, I have engaged in both crops and animal farm (poultry) supervision, agricultural project implementation, community engagement and education of rural farmers (women and youths) on both pre-harvest  and post-harvest management, and urban horticulture consultancy, giving me hands-on experience in crops production systems field management and pre harvest and post harvest challenges and technical mitigation strategies. \r\nHence, my combined expertise positions me to contribute meaningfully to teaching, curriculum development, student mentorship, applied research to help the university achieve its core mandate of raising highly skilled, innovative, and entrepreneurial graduates through practical, career-oriented technical education, applied research and industry collaboration for sustainable national development.', 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'Reading, listening to music and watching of movies', 'Immediately', 'I have actively participated in several international sustainability and intercultural learning programmes which have broadened my academic, professional and collaborative experiences. In November 2025, I participated in the UnaVEx global virtual exchange programme as a participant, in March 2026, I served as a facilitator in the same programme. I mentored and led seven students from Benin, Kenya, Scotland and Italy. In April 2026, I attended the Cleuvex virtual exchange programme on sustainability. These virtual exchange programmes were organised by the Helsinki University, Institute for Atmospheric and Earth System Research, in collaboration with other partners and co-sponsored under the Erasmus programme of the European Union. \r\nThese experiences provided me with valuable opportunities to interact, collaborate, and learn alongside students, researchers, and professionals from Europe, Asia, and Africa. They strengthened my exposure to multicultural learning environments, diverse perspectives, and global approaches to sustainability, innovation, and education. My active involvement in these programmes reflects my strong commitment to lifelong learning, innovation, sustainability, and inclusivity.\r\nIn addition, my participation in the Kumasi Tree Project (2024–2025) involved direct, on-site collaboration in Ghana between Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology (KNUST), Aalto University, and the Manhyia Palace of the Ashanti Kingdom. Through this project, I worked closely with visiting Finnish students and professors who came to Ghana to implement field-based activities. This experience significantly strengthened my international collaboration, communication, and teamwork skills in real-world, community-based sustainability work.\r\nI believe these combined experiences have equipped me with the global outlook, adaptability, and intercultural competencies necessary to contribute effectively to technical university education, particularly in agriculture, sustainability, and applied engineering-oriented learning.', 'Newton Kwaku Amaglo', 'Lecturer', 'Lecturer', 'Dr Newton Kwaku Amaglo\r\nP. O. Box 327 UP, Kumasi', '024 485 8258', 'newtonamaglo02@gmail.com', 'Prof. Paul Yaw Adjei', 'Lecturer', 'Professor', '27 Nana Kwafo Road, Tanoso Apatrapa.', '+233244589813', 'py.adjei@yahoo.com', 'Prof. Joseph Sarkodie-Addo', 'Lecturer', 'Professor', 'Ak-506 04-05, Kotei, Kumasi', '+233244576813', 'jaddosak@yahoo.com', 'BTU_112006F1_cv_6a15a5e4840d46.03729316.pdf', 'BAFIILE_E__A__CV_.pdf', 'pending', NULL, '154.160.20.180', '2026-05-26 13:53:40', '2026-06-07 23:59:41', 'BTU_112006F1_photo_6a15a5e4840d96.96764523.jpg', '1000640447.jpg'),
(91, 'BTU-C8222776', 14, 'Mr.', 'Frimpong', 'George', 'fgee2@yahoo.com', '+233246672196', 'Post Office Box KS 13453. Adum-Kumasi, Ashanti Region', 'Juaben', 'Juaben', 'Ashanti', 'Ghanaian', 'Christianity', 'married', 'Mrs. Mary Owusu Frimpong', 'Post Office Box KS 13453. Adum-Kumasi, Ashanti Region', NULL, 'P0016222695', 'GHA-717316135-6', '1984-06-02', 'male', 'Master\'s Degree (Other)', 'University of Education, Winneba (Kumasi Campus)', 11, 'The influence of implementation of Ghana\'s integrated financial management information system in senior high schools', 'The knowledge and experience that I have acquired over the years working as a Chartered Accountant and Chartered Tax Practitioner have prepared me enough to take up the role of an Accountant at the university in relation to financial preparations and budgeting as well as all the payroll and tax duties. \r\nAlso, the knowledge that I have gained over the years preparing donor fund reports would be put to bear when I am offered the opportunity. Moreso, my skill as a fast learner would help me to contribute to the progress of the university.', 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'Learning, listening to music (Adadam), cooking and having fruitful discussions', '1 month. This will enable me to prepare and formally part ways with my current employer', 'I am both a qualified Chartered Accountant and Chartered Tax Practitioner. I am also a member of the Institute of Internal Auditors, Ghana', 'Mr. Samuel Lartey Odame,', 'Accountancy', 'Head, Accounts Department', 'Post Office Box KS 13453. Adum-Kumasi, Ashanti Region', '0202411006', 'samuelodame3@gmail.com', '1.	Ms. Dina Ansaa Okyere', 'Auditor', 'Head, Internal Audit', 'Post Office Box KS 13453. Adum-Kumasi, Ashanti Region', '0203748984/054490344', 'afuaokyere@yahoo.com', '2.	Dr Richard Owusu- Afriyie', 'Lecturer/Auditing', 'Lecturer', 'Post Office Box KS 13453. Adum-Kumasi, Ashanti Region', '0244418800', 'richardowusuafriyie@ymail.com', 'BTU_C8222776_cv_6a15b7aa89ecb6.