(175, 'BTU-A259654B', 2, 'Dr.', 'ADONGO', 'AWINABA AMOAH', 'awinabaadongo@gmail.com', '+233249122566', 'Ejisuman Senior High School\r\nP. O. Box 46\r\nEjisu-Ashanti, Ghana\r\n29Th May 2026', 'KOLOGO, NAVRONGO', 'KOLOGO', 'Upper East', 'GHANAIAN', 'CHRISTIAN', 'married', 'EVELYN AKANTEGE', 'BOMFA METHODIST BASIC SCHOOL, BOMFA-JUABEN-ASHANTI', 'ROBERTINA ADONGO 17/09/2007\r\nROSEMOND ADONGO 17/12/2011\r\nROSSA AWINSUNE ADONGO 03/10/2014\r\nROBERT AWINABA ADONGO JNR 01/09/2019', '0021917914', 'GHA-71727158-0', '1977-03-03', 'male', 'PhD', 'KWAME NKRUMAH UNIVERSITY OF SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY', 3, '1.	Moro, A., Bodpii, D. N., Mokulogo, R. K., Adongo, A. A., Yar, D. D., &amp; Akazili, J. (2026). A Qualitative Investigation of Traditional Breastfeeding Practices Among Lactating Mothers in Northern Ghana. Journal of Human Lactation, 08903344261419354. \r\n2.	Adongo, A. A., Bodpii, D. N., Mokulogo, R. K., Chola, L., &amp; Akazili, J. (2026). Healthcare Infrastructure and Resource Barriers to Preventing Mother-to-Child Transmission of HIV in Ghana: Insights from a Qualitative Study. International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, 23(3), 293. https://www.mdpi.com/1660-4601/23/3/293 \r\n3.	Bempong, E; Aketema, J; Abdulai, D; Adongo A. A (2026). Effects of\r\nDeforestation on Environmental Degradation and Socio-Cultural Transformation in Akyem Abuakwa Traditional Area, located within the rainforest belt of Ghana. J. Appl. Sci. Environ. Manage. 30 (2) 402-409\r\n4.	Adongo, A. A., Mokulogo, R. K., Bodpii, D. N., Akazili, J., &amp; Yar, D. D. (2025). A patient-centred comparison of the public and private healthcare service quality: insights from the SERVQUAL model. Discover Health Systems, 4(1), 137. https://doi.org/10.1007/s44250-025-00317-4 \r\n5.	Adongo, A. A., Akuoko, K. O., Dapaah, J. M., &amp; Manful, E. (2025). Breastfeeding complexities and sociocultural barriers in the context of preventing perinatal transmission of HIV: A descriptive phenomenology in Northern Ghana. PLOS One https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0327353&amp;?utm_id=plos111&amp;utm_source=internal&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=author \r\n6.	Adongo, A. A., Akuoko, K. O., Dapaah, J. M., &amp; Manful, E. (2024). Experiences of health care providers in the sociocultural context of the prevention of mother-to-child transmission of HIV in Ghana: A descriptive phenomenology. Journal of HIV/AIDS &amp; Social Services, 1-26. https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/15381501.2024.2427278 \r\n7.	Adongo, A. A., &amp; de Paul Kanwetuu, V. (2024, November). The lived experiences of Women\'s identities and intersections in accessing social justice within the Ghanaian informal legal system: A phenomenological investigation. In Women\'s Studies International Forum (Vol. 107, p. 103005). Pergamon. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0277539524001432?casa_token \r\n8.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., &amp; Addo, B. (2024). HIV/AIDS-related knowledge, attitudes and perceptions of urban Ghanaian pregnant women: Results of a qualitative study. International Journal of Africa Nursing Sciences, 100785. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2214139124001318  \r\n9.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., Azumah, F. D., &amp; Onzaberigu J. N. (2024). Maternal and child health care access to skilled delivery services among Ghanaian rural mothers. Journal of Research in Health Services &amp; Regions https://doi.org/10.1007/s43999-024-00042-0  \r\n10.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., Azumah, F. D. (2024). Gender and Access to Justice in the Informal Court System in Ghana: A Descriptive Phenomenology in a Patriarchal Society. Journal of current social sciences, Vol.1, 1-15 https://www.eurekaselect.com/article/137967\r\n11.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., &amp; Azumah, F. D. (2023). Gender and leadership positions: Understanding women’s experiences and challenges in patriarchal societies in Northern Ghana. International Journal of Sociology and Social Policy, 43(11/12), 1114–1137. https://doi.org/10.1108/IJSSP-02-2023-0028\r\n12.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., Azumah, F. D., &amp; Onzaberigu J. N. (2022). The influence of socio-demographic behavioural variables on health-seeking behaviour and the utilisation of public and private hospitals in Ghana. International Journal of Sociology and Social Policy, 42(5/6), 455-472. https://doi.org/10.1108/IJSSP-03-2021-0068\r\n13.	Azumah, F. D., Onzaberigu, J. N., &amp; Adongo, A. A. (2023). Gender, agriculture and sustainable livelihood among rural farmers in northern Ghana. Economic Change and Restructuring, 56(5), 3257–3279. https://doi.org/10.1007/s10644-022-09399-z \r\n14.	Adongo, A. A., Dapaah, J. M., &amp; Wireko, D. (2022). The influence of family size on academic performance of high school students in Ghana. SN Social Sciences, 2(9), 179. https://doi.org/10.1007/s43545-022-00478-6\r\n15.	Adongo, A. A., Azumah, F. D., &amp; Onzaberigu, J. N. (2022). A comparative study of quality of health care services of public and private hospitals in Ghana. Journal of Public Health, 30(7), 1809–1815. https://doi.org/10.1007/s10389-021-01479-0', 'Teaching Philosophy and Research Interests\r\nDr Awinaba Amoah Adongo\r\nTeaching Philosophy\r\nMy teaching philosophy is rooted in a student-centred and transformative approach that equips learners with critical thinking skills and practical competencies to address real-world public health challenges. As a health sociologist, population health scientist, and social epidemiologist, I emphasize the application of sociological perspectives to understanding health behaviours, health systems, and inequalities, particularly within low- and middle-income contexts.\r\nI adopt diverse and interactive teaching strategies, including collaborative learning, inquiry-based learning, and case-based discussions. These approaches encourage students to actively engage with course material and apply theoretical concepts to practical situations. I integrate real-life case studies from Ghana’s healthcare system to make learning relevant and impactful. Additionally, I leverage digital tools such as PowerPoint presentations and guided discussions to enhance student participation, engagement, and comprehension.\r\nI have taught a range of undergraduate and postgraduate courses, including Medical Sociology, Human Reproductive Health, Public Health Gerontology, Family Programmes and Policies, Religion, Health and Society, Gender, Sexuality and Public Health, and Maternal, Neonatal, and Child Health, and Environmental Sociology. Through these courses, I aim to develop students’ analytical abilities, research competence, ethical reasoning, and problem-solving skills necessary for careers in public health, research, academia, and policy development.\r\nMy commitment extends beyond classroom instruction to student mentorship and research supervision. I co-supervise postgraduate research on topics such as maternal health, infectious diseases, mental health, and health systems strengthening. I guide students in developing rigorous research designs, applying appropriate methodologies, and producing high-quality academic work.\r\nDrawing from my background in secondary education, I have developed strong classroom management skills and the ability to communicate complex ideas clearly and effectively. I am committed to creating an inclusive, supportive, and intellectually stimulating learning environment that respects diversity, promotes active participation, and fosters lifelong learning.\r\nResearch Interests\r\nMy research focuses on the intersection of health sociology and public health, with particular emphasis on addressing health inequalities and improving population health outcomes in Ghana and similar contexts. My work contributes to understanding how social, cultural, behavioural, and institutional factors influence health behaviours, healthcare access, and service delivery.\r\nKey Research Interests\r\n•	Adolescent reproductive health \r\n•	Aging and health service utilization \r\n•	Behavioural change in health promotion \r\n•	Comparative healthcare systems \r\n•	Gender, human sexuality, and health \r\n•	Health challenges in low- and middle-income countries \r\n•	Health policy and health systems strengthening \r\n•	HIV/AIDS and infectious diseases \r\n•	Maternal, neonatal, and child health \r\n•	Mental health and social inequality \r\n•	Multilevel interventions for health promotion \r\n•	Organizational culture in healthcare settings \r\n•	Population health issues \r\n•	Public health education and health promotion \r\n•	Social determinants of health and public health outcomes \r\nI employ both qualitative and quantitative research methodologies, with strong expertise in phenomenological, community-based, and mixed-methods approaches. My research has been published in reputable peer-reviewed journals, including PLOS ONE, International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health, and International Journal of Sociology and Social Policy.\r\nMy studies have addressed important issues such as sociocultural barriers to breastfeeding and HIV prevention, disparities in healthcare service quality between public and private facilities, and challenges in maternal healthcare access. These works provide policy-relevant insights that support evidence-based decision-making and health system improvements.\r\nI am particularly interested in interdisciplinary collaborations and partnerships with universities, public health institutions, NGOs, and policymakers to translate research findings into practical interventions and evidence-based policies.\r\nConclusion\r\nMy teaching and research are closely aligned in their shared commitment to improving public health outcomes and addressing social inequalities. I remain committed to delivering high-quality teaching, mentoring students, and conducting impactful research that contributes to knowledge generation, policy development, and community wellbeing. I look forward to contributing meaningfully to the academic community through excellence in teaching, research, mentorship, and professional service.', 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'WATCHING DOCUMENTARY, RESEARCHING, WASHING', 'Within two weeks of notification.', 'I am highly motivated, hard-working, and willing to contribute effectively to the growth and success of the institution. I am also eager to learn and work collaboratively with others.', 'Professor Jonathan Mensah Dapaah', 'Lecturer', 'Senior Lecturer', 'Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology, Kumasi-Ghana\r\nDepartment of Sociology and Social Work', '+233249888048', 'jmdapaah.cass@knust.edu.gh', 'Professor Alhassan Sulemana Anamzoya', 'Lecturer', 'Head of Department of Sociology', 'University Of Ghana, Legon, Ghana\r\nDepartment of Sociology', '+233244564042.', 'asanamzoya@ug.edu.gh', 'Professor Eric Henry Yeboah', 'Lecturer', 'Senior Lecturer', 'Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology, Kumasi-Ghana\r\nDepartment of Sociology and Social Work', '+233559862658', 'eyeboah2@hotmail.com', 'BTU_A259654B_cv_6a19ae1e739f95.68121862.pdf', 'Abridged CV updated.pdf', 'pending', NULL, '154.161.251.225', '2026-05-29 15:17:50', '2026-06-07 23:59:41', 'BTU_A259654B_photo_6a19ae1e739fd7.42002801.jpg', 'Awinaba A.A Pastport 2019.JPG');
