(195, 'BTU-D279A2FD', 11, 'Mr.', 'ADINDAA', 'FREDERICK', 'fredrickadindaa@gmail.com', '0247441526', 'C/O DR. GILBERT ABONUSUN AYIMBIRE\r\nBOX, 767', 'YOROGO  GAABISI', 'BOLGATANGA', 'Upper East', 'GHANAIAN', NULL, 'married', 'Pricilla Ayamga Abotiba', 'YG10', 'WISDOM ADINDAA- 09/12/2019\r\nRANSFORD ADINDAA- 11/04/2021', NULL, 'GHA-723389599-3', '1985-06-02', 'male', 'Other', 'AKATURI JSS', 3, NULL, NULL, 'yes', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'Defensive drving\r\nlogistic and route planning', '2 months', NULL, 'GODWIN AKAPULE', 'TEACHER', 'FORM TEACHER', 'NYARIGA GIRLS JHS\r\nBOX 438', '0240266391', 'godwinakapule@gmail.com', 'DR. GILBERT ABONUSUN AYIMBIRE', 'LECTURER', 'HOD', 'BOLGATANGA TECHNICAL UNIVERSITY \r\nBOX 767', '0542252984', 'gilbertabonusun@gmail.com', 'DR. AKAPULE SAMUEL', 'LECTRER', 'NONE', 'BOLGATANGA TECHNICAL UNIVERSITY\r\nBOX767', '0547473606', 'samuelakapule@gmail.com', 'BTU_D279A2FD_cv_6a1ab967a753c3.83184026.pdf', 'ADINDAA.pdf', 'pending', NULL, '41.66.199.253', '2026-05-30 10:18:15', '2026-05-30 10:18:15', 'BTU_D279A2FD_photo_6a1ab967a75410.31137615.jpeg', 'WhatsApp Image 2026-05-30 at 9.03.50 AM.jpeg'),
(196, 'BTU-E2396067', 5, 'Mr.', 'IBRAHIM', 'YAHAYA', 'ijanena79@gmail.com', '+233245675696', 'Wa Technical Institute Box 238 Wa\r\nTA. 7 Wa Tagrayiri', 'Wa', 'WA', 'Upper West', 'Ghanaian', 'Islam', 'married', 'Bakyiko Lamatu', 'Wa Technical Institute Box 238 Wa', 'Saimaa Ibrahim Janjena                  18/6/2017\r\nHaaruun Ibrahim Janena                 11/11/2022\r\nFatima-Zaharaa Ibrahim Janjena      21/6/2024', 'P0016049551', 'GHA-715470320-9', '1979-03-17', 'male', 'Master\'s Degree (MPhil.)', 'Akenten Appiah-Menka University of Skills Training and Entrepreneurial Development', 11, 'A paper titled: Power Quality and   Performance Analysis of A 6.5 MW Lawra Solar PV Grid-Connected Power Systems is submitted to the Journal of Renewable Energies. It is under review. Another titled: Residential Grid-Connected Photovoltaics for Decarbonising Rural Households in Ghana: Energy Performance and Policy Insights, has been submitted to  ARDA PUBLICATION with paper ID: ARDA_ARDA__05_29_174538 which is also at the peer review stage.', 'My teaching, research, and professional experience have all been building towards an opportunity like this. Over the years, I have developed a deep passion for Electrical and Electronic Engineering, not just as a subject I teach, but as a field I actively research and practice.\r\nAcademically, I hold a Master of Philosophy in Electrical Power Systems Engineering and a Master of Technology in Electrical/Electronic Engineering, which have equipped me with both the depth of knowledge and the research skills necessary to contribute meaningfully at the tertiary level. My research has focused on real-world problems, from analysing the power quality of a 6.5MW solar PV grid-connected system in Lawra, to modelling the feasibility of grid-connected photovoltaic systems in Kpalwugu, to finding better ways to help students understand how to use an oscilloscope. These are not just academic exercises to me; they reflect a genuine interest in finding solutions that matter to our communities and improving the way engineering is taught.\r\nOn the professional side, I have spent over a decade teaching and leading at Wa Technical Institute, where I have taught subjects ranging from Digital Electronics and Circuit Analysis to Power Electronics and AC Circuit Theory. Leading the Electronic Engineering Department and serving as Academic Board Secretary has taught me how educational institutions work from the inside, and I bring that administrative and leadership experience with me.\r\nI also work with simulation tools like MATLAB/Simulink, ETAP, and HOMER regularly, and I have been involved in developing national CBT learning materials and assessment guidelines with CTVET, which means I understand curriculum design at a policy level. I am confident that all of this makes me well prepared and genuinely excited to contribute as a Lecturer.', 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'I genuinely enjoy reading, particularly books and materials related to engineering, energy systems, and technology. Keeping up with developments in renewable energy is something I do almost naturally because it connects directly to my research interest in solar power systems.\r\nI also have a strong passion for community service and working with young people. My years of involvement with the Ghana Muslim Students&#039; Association, rising from branch member to National Vice President, were not just titles to me. I truly enjoyed organising, mentoring students, and contributing to causes bigger than myself, and that spirit of service has never left me.\r\nI love working with simulation software like MATLAB and ETAP, sometimes just to explore ideas or test concepts out of curiosity, not necessarily for a project. It sounds unusual as a hobby, but for someone who loves engineering, it is genuinely enjoyable.\r\nI also enjoy travelling and meeting people from different backgrounds. My industrial attachment with the Electricity Company of Ghana in Accra, my studies in Kumasi and my work across different institutions have given me an appreciation for learning from diverse environments and people.\r\nAt the end of the day, I am someone who finds joy in learning, serving others, and solving problems, and I think those interests reflect who I am both inside and outside the classroom.', 'Approximately, one month', 'First, I am not just an electrical / electronic engineering teacher by qualification but by passion. From my early days as a student to my years of teaching and researching, I have always been drawn to understanding how things work and finding better ways to explain those concepts to others. That passion drives everything I do in the classroom and beyond.\r\nSecond, my involvement in the development of national CBT learning materials and assessment guidelines in collaboration with CTVET and Eljen Company has given me a broader perspective on technical and vocational education in Ghana. I understand the policy environment, the curriculum framework, and the standards expected at the national level, and I believe that insight will be an asset in a lecturing role.\r\nThird, I am a firm believer in continuous self-development. Pursuing two postgraduate degrees while working full time as a facilitator and Head of Department was not easy, but it reflects my determination to grow and give the best of myself to my students and institution.\r\nFinally, I am a team player with strong interpersonal skills. My years of leadership in both academic and community settings have taught me how to work with diverse groups of people, manage conflicts, and build consensus, qualities I believe are just as important in academia as technical knowledge.\r\nI am confident that I will be a valuable addition to your institution and I look forward to the opportunity to prove that.', 'Dr. Albert Kotawoke Awopone', 'Senior Lecturer', 'Head of Department Electrical and Electronic Engineering Education', 'University of Skills Training and Entrepreneurial Development (USTED). \r\nPost Office Box. 1277,\r\nTanoso - Kumasi', '+233-200784372', 'aawopone@aamusted.edu.gh', 'Dr. Patrick Nyaaba Ayambire', 'Teaching', 'Lecturer', 'University of Skills Training and Entrepreneurial Development (USTED). \r\nPost Office Box. 1277,\r\nTanoso - Kumasi', '+233-552424305', 'pnayambire@aamusted.edu.gh', 'Ing. Dr. Misbawu Adam', 'Teaching', 'Senior Lecturer', 'Kumasi Technical University\r\nPost Office Box 854, Kumasi, Ashanti Region', '+233- 542410107', 'adam.misbawu@kstu.edu.gh', 'BTU_E2396067_cv_6a1ae631990a24.25063531.pdf', 'MPHILS. CERT.pdf', 'shortlisted', '', '154.161.24.34', '2026-05-30 13:29:21', '2026-06-12 23:42:47', 'BTU_E2396067_photo_6a1ae631990a75.49362169.jpeg', 'PASSPORT.jpeg'),
