shawm. [music]. Internet Archive. https://archive.org/details/@daniel_helman\r\n\r\n    11. Helman, D.S. (2017, March 30). Flash Fiction: My iFriend. 365tomorrows. https://365tomorrows.com/2017/03/30/my-ifriend/\r\n\r\n    12. Helman, D.S. &amp; Haqq-Misra, J. (2017). Preserving Arctic and Antarctic ice: Ideas about artificial processes. In Proceedings of SUSCON-V, IIM Shillong, Shillong, India, 17-19 March 2016. https://www.academia.edu/34169642/Preserving_Arctic_and_Antarctic_Ice_Ideas_about_Artificial_Processes\r\n\r\n    13. Helman, D.S. (2016, October 6). Flash Fiction: Malia Read the Paper and Then Again. 365tomorrows. https://365tomorrows.com/2016/10/06/malia-read-the-paper-and-then-again/\r\n\r\n    14. Helman, D.S. (2016). Review of British Columbia\'s Inland Rainforest: Ecology, Conservation, and Management by Susan K. Stevenson et al. Electronic Green Journal. 1(39). https://escholarship.org/uc/item/0f0415w0\r\n\r\n    15. Helman, D.S. (2016). Recycled glass innovation: Ground glass as a pigment and filler material. In Proceedings of ICETETS 2016, Kings College of Engineering, Thanjavur, India, 24-26 February 2016. https://www.academia.edu/23133821/Recycled_glass_innovation_Ground_glass_as_a_pigment_and_filler_material\r\n\r\n    16. Helman, D.S. (2015). Scientific creativity to fuel sustainability: Teaching math and science in a way that inspires and heals. In Proceedings of RE-DO: Conference on sustainability and culture\'s role in sustainable futures, Aarhus, Denmark, 28-31 October, 2015. https://www.academia.edu/17432833/Scientific_Creativity_to_Fuel_Sustainability_Teaching_Math_and_Science_in_a_Way_that_Inspires_and_Heals\r\n\r\n    17. Helman, D.S. (2015). Ice as a novel material for solar panels in cold climates: Potential for adoption and usage. In Proceedings of ECPR General Conference, Université de Montréal, 26-29 August 2015. https://www.academia.edu/14824512/Ice_as_a_Novel_Material_for_Solar_Panels_in_Cold_Climates_Potential_for_Adoption_and_Usage\r\n\r\n    18. Helman, D.S. (2015). Review of Forest Economics by Daowei Zhang &amp; Peter H. Pearse. Electronic Green Journal, 1(38). https://escholarship.org/uc/item/0pb1r327\r\n\r\n    19. Helman, D.S. (2015). Finding nature, finding love. [poetry]. Journal of Sustainability Education, 7. http://www.jsedimensions.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Daniel-Helman-Finding-Nature-Finding-Love-PDF-Ready.pdf\r\n\r\n    20. Helman, D.S. (2015). Sixth Extinction, Here We Are. [song]. YouTube. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tM7xIpCZQkY\r\n\r\n    21. Helman, D.S. (2013). Review of Dry River: Stories of Life, Death, and Redemption on the Santa Cruz by Ken Lamberton. Electronic Green Journal, 1(36). https://escholarship.org/uc/item/5ks569g5\r\n\r\n    22. Helman, D.S. (2013). Review of Food and the Mid-Level Farm: Renewing an Agriculture of the Middle by Lyson, Stevenson &amp; Welsh (Eds.). Electronic Green Journal, 1(35). https://escholarship.org/uc/item/2pd0b604\r\n\r\n    23. Helman, D.S. (2011). Letter to the Editor: The levity of dark energy. Physics Today, 64(10), 10. doi:10.1063/PT.3.1276', 'My academic and professional trajectory aligns well with the Liberal Studies Department at Bolgatanga Technical University, particularly in the areas of Mathematics, ICT, and Computer Literacy within interdisciplinary and applied education contexts.\r\nTeaching Relevance\r\nAcross more than two decades of tertiary, secondary, and adult education teaching, I developed extensive experience in delivering foundational and cross-disciplinary courses that map directly onto Liberal Studies curricula. At institutions including Wofford College, College of Micronesia-FSM, Ton Duc Thang University, and multiple U.S. adult education systems, I have taught mathematics-adjacent content, science literacy, educational psychology, and ICT-relevant competencies in both classroom and online formats.\r\nFor example, the following courses at COM-FSM: Math Teaching Methods, Science Teaching Methods, Educational Psychology, and Assessment Design, and these show a sustained engagement with the pedagogical foundations required to support Liberal Studies students. My work consistently emphasizes numeracy, scientific reasoning, digital literacy, and transferable analytical skills—core competencies for technical university general education programs.\r\nMy experience teaching large, diverse student populations—including first-generation university students, adult learners, and pre-service teachers—has strengthened my capacity to deliver inclusive, accessible lessons aligned with the mission of producing industry-ready graduates.\r\nResearch Relevance\r\nMy research profile is interdisciplinary, spanning education, sustainability science, geoscience, ICT applications in learning, and computational thinking in education. A central theme of my research is the integration of scientific reasoning, computational approaches, and educational design, particularly in contexts where learners must bridge theory and applied problem-solving.\r\nRelevant peer-reviewed work includes studies on formative assessment in science education, educational technology usage across cultural contexts, and applied mathematical reasoning in interdisciplinary systems. This research directly supports curriculum development in Liberal Studies, especially where ICT integration and quantitative reasoning are required.\r\nI have also contributed to research on learning systems, digital communication in education, and applied data interpretation, which aligns with ICT literacy goals and the increasing need for students to develop computational fluency in technical universities.\r\nProfessional and Applied Experience\r\nMy professional background extends beyond academia into curriculum design, educational program development, grant writing, and institutional capacity building across multiple countries. At College of Micronesia-FSM, I served in roles involving accreditation support, curriculum revision, and educational policy implementation—experience directly relevant to institutional academic quality assurance at Bolgatanga Technical University.\r\nI have also led and participated in interdisciplinary research projects involving ICT systems for education delivery, including distance learning infrastructure and online pedagogy development. These experiences are particularly relevant to Liberal Studies programs that aim to integrate ICT into general education and enhance student digital competencies.\r\nThank you!', 'no', 'no', NULL, 'no', NULL, 'Art, yoga, choir, dance, bicycles, hiking, travel.', 'Immediately', NULL, 'Dr. Svetoslav Georgiev', 'Academia', 'Associate Professor', 'Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University\r\nSchool of Intelligent Finance and Business\r\n7PFQ+W6 Xietangzhen\r\nWuzhong District\r\nSuzhou, Jiangsu, China', '+86 (0)512 88970739', 'Svetoslav.Georgiev@xjtlu.edu.cn', 'Dr. Alessandro Fergnani', 'Academia', 'Assistant Professor', 'National University Singapore\r\nSchool of Business\r\n15 Kent Ridge Dr.\r\nSingapore 119245', '+65 83167730', 'alessandro.fergnani@gmail.com', 'Dr. John Hutnyk', 'Academia', 'Associate Professor', 'Ton Duc Thang University\r\n19 Nguyen Huu Tho\r\nTan Phong, Quan 7\r\nHo Chi Minh City, Vietnam', '+84 (028) 37 755 063', 'johnhutnyk@tdtu.edu.vn', 'BTU_3C1D6E8E_cv_6a1f436c7d04b6.24002582.pdf', 'CV Daniel Helman May 2026.pdf', 'pending', NULL, '76.95.172.19', '2026-06-02 20:56:12', '2026-06-07 23:59:41', 'BTU_3C1D6E8E_photo_6a1f436c7d0508.23848969.jpg', 'Daniel Ring Portrait small 420 x 530.jpg'),
