(576, 271, 'May 2025', 'Dec. 2023', 'Agronome et Veterinarians Sans Frontieres (AVSF)', 'Tarkwa, Western Region, Ghana', 'Facilitator in Structuring Cocoa Cooperatives', '1. Draw up reference situation following an organizational diagnosis of the partner Cooperative\r\n2. Facilitate sessions to review the articles of association and internal control systems\r\n3. Facilitate the establishment of income Generating Activities (IGAs)\r\n4. Training on cooperatives life\r\n5. Training on cooperatives Management\r\n6. Training in group sales and commercial prospecting\r\n7. Sales canvassing, participating in trade fairs and exhibitions (Sara, salon du chocolate etc)\r\n8. Process for the creation of a cooperative union\r\n9. Draw up a strategic development plan and procedures manual\r\n10. Organize exchange visits to Equite partner cooperatives\r\n11. Organize workshops to identify needs and set up IGAs\r\n12. Support union with equipment and materials (Tricycles, office space, etc.)\r\n13. Organize business plan development workshops\r\n14. Draw up a guide to running and structuring cooperatives\r\n15. Training in traceability and data management practices', '', 'Contract Ended', 0),
(577, 271, 'October 20', NULL, 'Shea Network-Ghana (SNG)', 'Tamale, Northern Region, Ghana', 'National Coordinator', '. QUALITY LEADERSHIP &amp; ORGANIZATIONAL MANAGEMENT \r\n1. Shall be the vision bearer and provide visionary leadership along the vision of the organization, facilitate revision of strategic plan, constitutional amendment, and communication strategy among others.\r\n2. Provide mentorship and coaching support to young staff to ensure they learn on the job \r\n3. Provide quality representation and serve as the mouthpiece to articulate the organization position and resolves among alliances and partners as well as other stakeholders\r\n4. Assume overall management responsibilities for the SNG Secretariat, ensuring smooth operation and effective utilization of resources. \r\n5. Ensure organization compliance with statutory organization such as SSNIT, IRS Registrar General and District Assemblies among others\r\n6. Ensure that accounting system is very functional and Audited accounts\r\n7. Provide leadership for all consultants or funding coalitions developed with SNG as lead organization.\r\n\r\nVALUE-CHAIN COORDINATION &amp; MEMBER SERVICES \r\n\r\n1. Facilitate access to technical and capacity building support for key value chain players\r\n2. Explore and introduce innovation that will enable members to access the market both locally and internationally including the facilitation and organization of Trade Fairs among similar activities \r\n3. Co-coordinate project activities aimed at improving industry visibility, inclusion of shea collectors, and conservation of shea resources.\r\n4. Facilitate the organization and holding of SNG Annual General Meetings to engage stakeholders, review progress, and plan future initiatives. \r\n5. Collaborate with national and international networks to foster synergies, share best practices, and advocate for the interests of the shea value chain. \r\n6. Explore opportunities for market access for members\r\n\r\nPOLICY ADVOCACY &amp; INFLUENCING \r\n\r\n1. Ensure SNG visibility and inputs in sector polices both national and local that support the shea Sector \r\n2. Ensure SNG voice and position is made clear in policy dialogues \r\n3. Facilitate the holding of periodic planning and meetings to assess progress, identify challenges, and devise strategies for policy advocacy. \r\n4. Develop policy briefs and share with keep stakeholders \r\n5. Track all SNG legacy advocacy and policy engagements for follow ups. \r\n6. Ensure functional structures for the organization women mass movements to participate in national advocacy issues.\r\n\r\nFUND RAISING &amp; PROJECT MANAGEMENT.\r\n\r\n1. Develop co-creation partnerships with SNG initial promoters and position SNG in their funding spaces \r\n2. Facilitate the development of Expression of interest, Concept notes and proposals to bid for grants \r\n3. Introducing a strategy to get members to pay dues and exploit fees paying for conferences\r\n4. Responsible for overall implementation of all ongoing and upcoming donor grants', 'full-time', NULL, 1),
(578, 271, 'March 2024', NULL, 'EBNA Royal Consult', 'Tamale, Northern Region, Ghana', 'Operations Specialist', '1. Monitored day-to-day operations at the organization\r\n2. Analyzed staff activities in the field and proposed measures to advance change for development \r\n3. Handle all project beneficiaries’ issues and ensure measures are taken to address them\r\n4. Provide essential technical support in the acquisition of pressing machines, Motor tricycles, virgin bottles, veronica buckets and PPEs for cashew apple processing\r\n5. Ensured smooth operations of the 30 SMEs in cashew apple processing and provide administrative support.\r\n6. Co-developed cashew apple processing and Health, Safety and hygiene manuals\r\n7. Facilitated capacity building training on cashew apple processing for 30 SMEs\r\n8. Supported in concept note and detailed proposal development\r\n9. Trained 30 women on Health, Safety and Hygiene for 30 SMEs\r\n10. Identified opportunities for improvement of EBNA Royal Consult Limited operations.\r\n11. Supervise the opening of bank accounts\r\n\r\nEnhancing environmental safety through regulation and safe use of agrochemicals, fertilizers, disposal and recycling of used containers under Market Systems Resilient (MSR) Activity\r\n\r\nAchievements: \r\n1. Support in profiling of beneficiaries for the project\r\n2. Supported to develop questionnaire and carry out baseline data collection for farmers, Spraying Service Providers and stakeholder institutions\r\n3. Supported in the analysis of the data to come out with findings \r\n4. Facilitated and presented the baseline findings to stakeholders at Mion, Yendi, Gushegu, Yagaba, Gambaga and Tempane Districts\r\n5. Supported to develop a training manual used in training Farmers, Spraying Service Providers, Input Dealers and Scrap Dealers\r\n\r\nImproved Productivity through Smallholder Access to Fertilizer and other Agriculture inputs under the USAID Feed the Future Ghana Mobilizing Financing in Agricultural (MFA)\r\n\r\n Achievements: \r\n1. Supported to assist VSLAs to identify appropriate locations for input shops in their communities and help to establish these shops for the purpose of selling agricultural inputs, including fertilizer. \r\n2. Supported to provide technical oversight in the setting up of the shops, including shop rental, basic fit out of shelving, shop branding, and other miscellaneous activities required to have a functional shop. \r\n3. Supported to facilitate linkage with input dealers to provide training on proper handling of fertilizer and other production inputs. \r\n4. Supported to hand hold VSLAs to successfully operate one cycle of the input shop and provide the needed training required to manage the shop.', 'full-time', NULL, 2),
(579, 271, 'Sept. 2020', NULL, 'AVSF - Ghana', 'NationWide', 'National Technoical Assistant (NTA)', 'Achievements:\r\n1. Supported in Concept note development for producer organizations (ACCOPPS/AMMOPPA cooperative in pineapple production, ABOCFA in organic cocoa production, Kuapa kokoo in cocoa production, BS Abanga coconut society in coconut production and Fanteakwa farmer’s union in organic cocoa production)\r\n2. Supported 7 Producer Organizations to develop winnable proposals for up to 250,000 Euros \r\n3. Monthly reports writing on project activities monitored at producer organizations level.\r\n4. Supported in the practices of dynamic Agroforestry for cocoa cooperatives at Kuapa Kokoo in Ghana.\r\n5. Supported in securing Agroforestry seedlings as part of the Equity II Project implementation for Abekoase cocoa society at Fanteakwa Union to do cocoa Agroforestry.\r\n6. Assisted and continuous monitoring of project implementation with Producer Organizations that won projects\r\n7. Ensured all principles and regulations regarding Fairtrade and Organic certification are adhered,\r\n8. Advice Donors, project partners and stakeholders on strategies for sustainable development methods and processes to enhance businesses that are Agro-ecologically minded \r\n9. Ensured gender equity and youth development in Agribusiness at producer organization is maintained,\r\n10. Supported in setting up nursery for Agroforestry build up at ABOCFA as part of the Equity II project in Ghana\r\n11. Provided technical support to 7 Producer Organizations (POs) in climate change management, agro-ecological practices and biodiversity management\r\n12. Carried out performance monitoring in line with budgets and impact Evaluations of producer Organizations\r\n13. Conducted baseline survey at producer organizations level to ascertain the level of productivity before the project implementation', 'full-time', NULL, 3),
(580, 272, '2021', NULL, 'HEMANG-BUOHO TECHNICAL INSTITUTE OF GHANATVET SERVICE', 'P O. BOX SE 995 SUAME-KUMASI. ASHANTI REGION', 'ACCOUNTANT', 'WRITE AND AQUINT PAYMENT VOUCHERS, MAINTAIN UP TO  DATE CASH BOOKS, MAINTAIN BANK RECONCILIATION, PREPARE PERIODIC FINANCIAL REPORTS, WORK WITH THE INTERNAL AUDIT AND THE AUDIT SERVICE ETC.', 'full-time', NULL, 0),
(581, 273, 'May 2022', 'April 2022', 'Youth Challenge International', 'Youth Challenge International (YCI), Ghana Tamale, Ghana', 'Project Partnership and Training Coordinator', 'As a Partnership and Training Coordinator, I lead trainings, coordinate youth and women empowerment programmes in partnership with Bolgatanga Technical University, government agencies, community leaders, and local authorities, ensuring effective implementation and alignment with organisational objectives. \r\nOversee office administrative activities, including records management, documentation, scheduling, correspondence, logistics coordination, and stakeholder communication to support efficient programme operations. \r\nManage Canadian volunteer supervision, training delivery, safeguarding compliance, and field coordination while maintaining accurate data, reports, and operational records. \r\nSupport monitoring, evaluation, and reporting processes, contributing to informed decision-making, accountability, and continuous program improvement.', 'full-time', 'Better opportunities.', 0),
(582, 273, 'April 2017', NULL, 'CAMFED Ghana', 'CAMFED Ghana Block A, No. 191 Choggu-Yapalse Tamale, Ghana.', 'Upper East Regional project Coordinator/Transitions Core Trainer', 'At CAMFED Ghana, I coordinated education and social empowerment programming across Northern Ghana, working closely with schools, community leaders, government stakeholders, and development partners to ensure effective program implementation. \r\nProvided administrative and operational support through planning, scheduling, documentation, records management, correspondence, and stakeholder coordination. \r\nOrganized meetings, workshops, and community engagement activities while maintaining accurate program records, reports, and communication materials. \r\nSupported monitoring, reporting, and accountability processes, contributing to informed decision-making and effective program delivery. Facilitated training and mentoring activities, supervised community-based structures, and strengthened partnerships to promote educational access, youth development, and community participation.', 'full-time', NULL, 1),
(583, 276, 'June 2018', NULL, 'Catholic Relief Services', 'Tamale', 'Senior Project Officer', '•	Effectively oversaw the Safe WASH Project\'s planning and execution, acting as the main point of contact between CRS and affiliated groups to guarantee smooth cooperation and the accomplishment of project goals.\r\n•	Enhanced access to safe water and sanitation services by effectively leading strategic community mobilization initiatives and supervising the implementation of WASH operations throughout targeted communities and institutions.\r\n•	 Oversaw biweekly technical meetings with funders, ensuring transparency and conformity with donor expectations while providing progress updates via comprehensive PowerPoint reports.\r\n•	Ensured cost-effectiveness and operational efficiency by developing thorough scopes of work and activity budgets for institutional and community-level WASH programs.\r\n•	Oversaw quarterly financial projections and kept a precise budget tracker to keep tabs on spending and direct the distribution of resources.\r\n•	 Managed the Safe WASH Project\'s whole budget, including variance analysis, performance reviews, and reporting to the Programs Director to aid in strategic decision-making.\r\n•	 Maintained fiscal responsibility and discipline throughout the project lifetime by ensuring that budget performance matched donor criteria and planned activities.\r\n•	Coordinated and oversaw four prosperous sales bazaars in Greater Tamale project communities, advancing access to reasonably priced sanitation goods and services.\r\n•	Oversaw the installation of more than 100 home toilets in project and non-project communities, assisting partner employees, sales representatives, and craftspeople in enhancing environmental health and sanitation coverage.\r\n•	Oversaw WASH Clubs, WASH Mentors, and Ghana Education Service (GES) partners at project schools, which led to the installation of 72 handwashing stations and improved staff and student hygiene habits.\r\n•	 Developed and led several workshops to increase the capacity of important stakeholders, such as School Management Committees, WASH Mentors, and WASH Clubs, giving them the tools they need to continue WASH initiatives and encourage climate-aware behavior.\r\n•	 Oversaw two donor technical team trips to Ghana, offering daily project site supervision and direct knowledge of project milestones and community effects.\r\n•	 Oversaw the examination and revision of the sanitation bylaws of the Tamale Metropolitan Assembly (TaMA), fortifying the legal foundations for environmental preservation and sanitation enforcement.\r\n•	To improve operational effectiveness and service delivery in the Greater Tamale area, I oversaw the development and implementation of Icesspool, a digital coordination platform for bulk water distributors, sanitation service providers, and vacuum truck operators (VTOs).', 'full-time', NULL, 0),
(584, 278, 'Oct. 2009', NULL, 'Ghana Health Service', 'Upper East Region, Bolgatanga', 'Medical Laboratory Scientist', 'I supervise multidisciplinary laboratory teams, evaluate technical competencies, and design and facilitate regional rollout and diagnostic refresher trainings to enhance staff performance.\r\nI manage the interface between the laboratory, clinicians, and patients, ensuring that customer inquiries, service turn-around times, and quality expectations are consistently met.\r\nI coordinate daily laboratory workflows, manage equipment and inventory, and ensure the seamless delivery of high-quality diagnostic services under minimal supervision.\r\nI perform advanced laboratory analyses and diagnostic procedures, utilizing my specialized expertise in clinical microbiology and malaria microscopy to provide accurate patient results.\r\nI oversee laboratory operations across regional and district facilities.', 'full-time', NULL, 0),
(585, 278, 'March 2009', NULL, 'Siloam Hospital', 'Kumasi, Ashanti Region', 'Biomedical Scientist', 'Performed high-complexity analytical testing on blood, tissue, and bodily fluids across major laboratory disciplines to aid in disease diagnosis and monitoring.\r\nExecuted daily quality control, calibrate and troubleshoot sophisticated instrumentation, and maintain strict adherence to SOPs and regulatory standards.\r\nManaged inventory, perform preventative equipment maintenance, and strictly enforce biosafety and infection control protocols.', 'full-time', NULL, 1),
(586, 279, 'March 2024', 'March, 201', 'University of Pardubice', 'Studentska 200, Polabiny, Pardubice, Czech Republic', 'External University Lecturer', 'Courses taught include Financial aspects of innovation, Microeconomics and Macroeconomics. Responsibilities include designing sylabus and a study guide for Financial aspects of innovation under the guidance of course guarantor. Delivering the lecture and assessing students in both written and oral examination,', 'full-time', 'To focus on my research firm at Capital Research', 0),
(587, 279, 'January 20', 'September ', 'Capital Research', 'Accra, Greater Accra region, Plot 2 Naa Otobia street, Darkuman', 'Research Cordinator', 'Assisted clients with project conceptualization and development of \r\nevaluation plans \r\n• Provided data analysis support to clients, including the application of \r\nquantitative techniques such as time series analysis, factor analysis, \r\nstructural equation modeling, and a range of bivariate and multivariate \r\nanalyses', 'full-time', 'I got a data collection contract job', 1),
